In a world with Dan Rather, and as Wired Magazine pulls numerous\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#articles for fake quotes[1], as conservatives are rocked by the\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#scandal of conflicting interests (being paid to write, or being\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#paid for similar things), and numerous similar things, I wonder\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#how John Leo can, with a straight face, tell us that we will lack\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#accountability and verification in the absence of traditional news\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#sources.[2] I am not one to discount the service they provide,\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#though I often do disparage them. After all, how many of my posts\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#would exist without the major news source to back it up? And I am\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#not so foolish as to think Townhall.com could pay all that many\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#of the journalists whose columns make up most of the rest of my\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#posts. Still, time and time again, we have seen a *lack*\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#of verification happening in the traditional news media, which,\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#to me, says that things could not be *worse* if we had\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#to categorize our news by how much we trust the source instead\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#of being told we can blindly trust the media. Which reminds me,\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#he seems to share this idea with much of the media "elite" that in\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#the absence of media to tell us what is important, what is true, we\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#would not question it for ourselves. He worries that there would\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#be a higher percentage of gossip and rumor accepted as fact, but\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#we have endured months of speculation over what President Bush's\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#Social Security plan would be, when he had released no details.\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#Who double checks the media? It was hugely noteworthy when ABC\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#decided to investigate "American Idol," hugely noteworthy because it\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#so rarely happens that anyone seriously questions the credibility\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#of a major network. Or at least, no one except the populace who,\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#apparently, are choosing to find their news elsewhere.

