On a side note, is this barrage of national and international news\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#even good for us? We all know about the international problems, we\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#hear nightly about the latest horrors, but who knows what happened\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#in their own town? Could you tell me who was married in your\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#parish this weekend? I could not, could you tell me who moved\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#out in your neighborhood this week? Who moved in? The barrage\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#of national and international news, the barrage of sensationalism,\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#is depressing, I cannot stand to watch it on the television, and I\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#read it online only out of boredom, I am aware it really is not all\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#that good for me (except to the extent that I do find motivation to\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#write about it and thus exercise my intellect in some minimal way).\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#Perhaps in the absence of the major news sources there would be\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#fewer investigations of Global Warming, perhaps we would be less\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#likely to know of the problems in the Congo. But then too, perhaps\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#we would be less interested in solving everything at a Federal level\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#and more interested in the decisions our Board of Supervisors make.\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#We would be more interested in the programs going on in our parishes.\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#We would be more interested in these things because they *are*\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#accessible to the unfunded individual, they *are* immediate\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#to our lives, and so would continue to make its way to our daily\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#intake of news. When the overall volume decreases, the noise to\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#signal ratio simply cannot stay constant, people, with less to\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#wade through, will more quickly learn what to pay attention to.

